```
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class Enemy : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float enemyLifetime = 6f;

    void Update()
    {
        enemyLifetime -= Time.deltaTime;
        if (enemyLifetime <= 0f) {
            Destroy(this.gameObject);
        }
    }
}
```
In the 'Buggy Code Line' section, the `Enemy` class has an `Update()` method that is called each frame, which is inefficient and can cause performance issues. The `Destroy()` method is called in the `Update()` method, which destroys the game object the `Enemy` script is attached to.

To fix the bug, the `Destroy()` method should be called in a more appropriate location, such as in the `Start()` method or in the `FixedUpdate()` method. Alternatively, the `Destroy()` method can be called at specific times or under specific conditions, such as when the enemy is out of health or when the enemy is triggered by the player's actions.

Here's the fixed code:
```
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class Enemy : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float enemyLifetime = 6f;

    void Start()
    {
        enemyLifetime = 6f;
    }

    void FixedUpdate()
    {
        enemyLifetime -= Time.deltaTime;
        if (enemyLifetime <= 0f) {
            // Destroy the enemy game object
            Destroy(this.gameObject);
        }
    }
}
```

